Let and var parameters of Javascript are not being colorized properly when used as part of a longer word/parameter inside a function.

![parametercolor](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12900364/13649641/7e700b2c-e5f3-11e5-9427-eacbcde85757.JPG)

`fcamelCase = function( all, letter, lettuce, constest ) {
        var variance = letter.toUpperCase();
        return variance;
    };`

This is effecting the latest Alpha build (0.10.12-alpha)

Syntax hightlighting for JavaScript breaks if a variable used inside a template string escape sequence starts with the characters "var":

``` javascript
var objid, varname;
{
    console.log(`${objid}.${varname}`);
}
thisPartIsWrong();
```

Here, the variable name `varname` is incorrectly highlighted, the "var" part is highlighted in the keyword color, while the rest of the variable name is colored correctly. After the template string, all remaining code is colored in the string color.

![vscode-highlighting-bug](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5391834/13643515/9a63e41a-e621-11e5-92c9-a050cb167492.png)

This is only true if the variable's name starts with "var" or "let". If any other keyword is used, e.g. "constname", "ifname", there is no error. if there is no wrapping block statement around the code containing the template string, the error also doesn't appear.
